0.header:
With vertigo it would feel as if the world is spinning around you.

This may be related to problems with the inner ear or to the brain.


Now, let's see how we can help

10.header: In addition to feeling dizzy, which of these are you also experiencing right now?

options.title: Cannot move my arm or leg

10.except: Oops!,You told me nothing

11.header:
None of these?
Good. We just ruled out having to go to the emergency room.

Just a few more questions for you before we see what a pharmacist can recommend for vertigo over-the-counter.

12.header:
Seek emergency room visit.

Here is why:

  • Something serious may be going on.

You should NOT continue if you answered correctly.

If it is not the correct choice, please return to the options page and choose again.

20.header:
Have you been diagnosed with vertigo before?

Or this is your first time experiencing spinning movements.

21.header:
If you are experiencing it now, we have a few advice on what to do below.

Keep these in mind when experiencing symptoms:

  • Keep still. Sit or lie down when symptoms occur.
  • Gradually resume activity.
  • Avoid sudden position changes.
  • Do not try to read when symptoms occur.
  • Avoid bright lights.
  • You may need help walking when symptoms occur.
  • Avoid hazardous activities such as driving, operating heavy machinery, and climbing until 1 week after symptoms have disappeared.

Let see what a pharmacist suggest you do that is available over-the-counter. Or would you like to go to a nearby urgent care clinic?

Or perhaps do you want to continue and refresh your understanding of vertigo for now?

22.header: Well, let's find out if you are looking at vertigo before we continue.

30.header: Which of the symptoms listed below are you experiencing?

options.title: Feeling room is moving or spinning

30.except: Oops!,You told me nothing

31.header:
None of these?
May not be looking at vertigo. Those are the signs and symptoms of vertigo.

Would you like to continue with vertigo or see the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

32.header:
Alright.
These are symptoms of vertigo.

With vertigo, you will see the world spinning around you like you just got off a fast merry go round.

Let's continue or would you like to see the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

40.header:
Are you currently taking any of these groups of medications?

Aminoglycosides
Gentamicin
Diuretics
Furosemide
Salicylates
Aspirin
Sedatives

Others
Quinine
Aniticonvulsants
high doses of dilantin, primidone
Antidepresants

Antihypertensives

41.header:
Yes?
At high doses they can cause ototoxicity which can lead to vertigo.

If the vertigo started after you started these medications or if it continues, discuss this with your doctor.

42.header: Are you diabetic?

43.header:
Yes?
Very low blood sugar can cause dizziness which can be confused with vertigo.

Just starting a new diabetic drug or increasing the dose of the current one you are taking can lower the blood sugar level making you feel dizzy.

If you are also sweating, suspect this and discuss it with your doctor as soon as possible.

Always check your blood sugar level and make sure it is at recommended levels.

44.header:
Are you a female of child bearing age?

If so have you taken a pregnancy test?

You might be pregnant and not know it.

45.header:
Yes?
Being pregnant and not knowing it can make you experience vertigo symptoms..

46.header: Have you checked your blood pressure lately?

47.header:
Very good.
Low blood pressure can cause symptoms similar to vertigo.

Know that increasing the dose of a blood pressure medication can cause symptoms similar to vertigo.

48.header:
Remember
Low blood pressure can make you feel dizzy and lightheaded.

Do you have a thyroid disorder?

49.header:
Yes?
Intolerance to heat or cold or weight changes can mimic the symptoms of vertigo.

We suggest you discuss this with your doctor.

50.header:
Other causes of vertigo include meniere's disease, migraine, multiple sclerosis among others.

If vertigo is persistent or troublesome for you, make sure you call the doctor for a detailed evaluation.

Let's see what a pharmacist suggest you take for vertigo over-the-counter until you can talk to a doctor. Or do you think you should seek urgent care from the discussions so far?

0.header:
A toothache may be caused by tooth decay, inflamed pulp or erupting wisdom tooth.

There are other causes of toothache such as sinus pain affecting the tooth, earache or even a heart attack coming on.


Let's see what will get you relief over the counter until you see a dentist at least.

We will start by ruling out medical emergencies.

1.header: Did this toothache start as a chest pain that moved to the arm and then to the teeth?

3.header:
Did it start with a chest pain that moved to the jaw, neck and then to the teeth?

It may have felt like a tight band around your chest or like something heavy sitting on your chest. Now you have jaw pain and toothache.

4.header:
Emergency!
Call 911.

Here is why:

  • You may be looking at a heart attack in progress.

Note:
We do not advice continuing. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

5.header:
It was important to rule out something like a heart attack.

Sometimes, a heart attack can be the cause of a toothache. It is the responsible thing to rule out any possibilities and not take anything for granted.

Let's continue

7.header: With this toothache, do you also have pain near the ear?

9.header: What about cracking sound when you chew something?

10.header:
Yes?
Possible TMJ syndrome. This condition affects the jaw.

You will have to see a doctor or dentist on this one.

11.header: Do you feel the tooth pain after stimulation from hot drinks or food?

12.header:
Yes?
You may be looking at tooth decay (dental caries).

13.header: Are you feeling the toothache after stimulation from cold drinks or food?

14.header:
Yes?
Possible tooth decay. (dental caries)

Bacteria that live in your mouth work on the sugars and carbs on your teeth to form a sticky plaque that stick to the surface of your teeth.

With time, the acid in the plaque erodes your tooth's coating leading to tiny openings called cavities on the surface.

The first sign of a decay may be a sensation when you eat sweet, very cold or very hot stuff. You need to see a dentist before it gets worse.

Pain may be isolated to a single tooth and usually stops when the stimulus is removed.

Would you like to see the nearest dentist to you or continue for now?

15.header: Is it after stimulation from sweet food or drink?

16.header:
Yes?
Possible tooth decay (dental caries) going on.

The first sign of a tooth decay may be a sensation when you eat sweet, very cold or very hot stuff.

You need to see a dentist before it gets worse.

Do you want to see a nearby dentist to you or continue for now?

17.header:
Alright.
Let's see if you are looking at a tooth infection or something else.

20.header: Is there swelling around the teeth or gums?

21.header:
Seek urgent care or call the dentist.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at an infection or a dental abscess.

22.header: Is there swelling in your face?

23.header:
Seek urgent care or call the dentist.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at an infection or a dental abscess.

24.header: Do you feel sharp pain on release from a chewing stroke?

25.header:
Seek urgent care or call the dentist.

Here is why:

  • You may be looking at a loose crown
  • May be looking at incomplete fracture of the crown of a vital tooth.

26.header: Is your tooth very sensitive to cold?

27.header:
Yes?
Possible loose crown or incomplete fracture of the crown of a vital tooth.

You should see a dentist as soon as possible. The toothache won't go away with over-the-counter measures.

28.header:
Are some of your teeth (molars, premolars) sensitive...

...When chewing and moving your mouth?

30.header:
Do you feel tooth pain when lowering the head?

Example when tying shoe laces?

31.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • You may be looking at sinusitis
  • Your sinuses may be inflamed.

32.header: Did you hit your teeth or mouth against something recently?

33.header:
See a dentist as soon as possible.

Here is why:

  • You must have chipped a tooth.
  • A tooth may be loose in its socket.

34.header:
With a toothache, you will have to see a dentist.

Anything over-the-counter is to help with the pain until you can see a dentist. Would you like to see what a pharmacist recommend for dental pain over-the-counter or see a nearby dental clinic to you?

18.title: Cold sores
dlg:
A typical cold sore goes through 5 stages from when it is formed to going away in about 1 to 2 weeks. The stages include:

  1. Tingling or Prodrome stage
  2. Blistering stage
  3. Weeping or oozing stage
  4. Scabbing stage and
  5. Healing stage

Cold sore is very contagious. So keep in mind the risk of transmitting the cold sore virus while you are at it. Take special care to avoid contact with infants.

0.header:
It is also called fever blisters. Let's take a look.

How do you know you have cold sores anyway?

Let's see what you are looking at.

1.header: Are you looking at small fluid-filled blisters?

3.header: Are there blisters that are red, raised a little from the skin surface?

4.header:
Yes?
Cold sores can present this way. This is a sign.

Signs include:

  • Small fluid-filled blisters.
  • Red and raised a little.

5.header: Are you seeing blisters that are yellow or crusty?

6.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of a cold sore.

Cold sores can be:

  • Small fluid filled
  • Red and raised a little
  • Yellow and crusty

7.header: What about small blisters filled with clear yellowish fluid?

8.header:
Yes?
This can be a sign of a cold sore.

Cold sores can be:

  • Small fluid filled
  • Red and raised a little
  • Yellow and crusty
  • Blisters with clear yellowish fluid

9.header: Are you looking at leaking blisters?

10.header:
Yes?
You are more than likely looking at a cold sore.

Cold sores can be:

  • Small fluid filled
  • Red and raised a little
  • Yellow and crusty
  • Blisters with clear yellowish fluid
  • Leaking blisters

11.header:
Alright.
Those were some of the physical signs of a cold sore.

If you think you may be looking at a cold sore, let's continue. Else, you will want to see a doctor for further evaluation.

Do you want to continue or see the nearby urgent care clinic to you?

20.header: Where do you have the blister or rash?
20.except: Oops!, You told me nothing

21.header:
None of these?
You will have to see a healthcare provider for further evaluation.

22.header:
Near the eyes?
You will have to see a doctor for this.

Herpes infection may be severe and dangerous if it occurs in or near the eye.

This is a leading cause of blindness in the United States as it causes scarring of the cornea.

Would you like to visit the nearest urgent care or continue for now?

23.header:
Alright.
A few more questions to determine the scope of this cold sore.

30.header:
Did you experience tingling or burning near the lips or mouth area?

Before the blister or blisters appeared?

31.header:
You did?
This is one of the warning signs of a cold sore.

32.header: What about itching of the lips or skin around the mouth?

33.header:
Yes?
This is a warning sign of a cold sore.

Warning signs include:

  • Tingling or burning near the lips or mouth area
  • Itching of the lips or skin around the mouth

34.header: If this is on the lips, is the whole lip swollen?

35.header:
Yes?
You may be looking at an insect bite or allergic reaction.

You should go to the nearest urgent care clinic.

36.header: Did you have a sore throat before the blisters appeared?

37.header:
Yes?
Sore throat sometimes occur before the blisters of a cold sore.

Warning signs of a cold sore include:

  • Tingling or burning near the lips or mouth area
  • Itching of the lips or skin around the mouth
  • Sometimes a sore throat

38.header: Any fever before the blisters appeared?

39.header:
Yes?
Warning sign of a cold sore. Hence the name fever blisters.

Warning signs include:

  • Tingling or burning near the lips or mouth area
  • Itching of the lips or skin around the mouth
  • Sometimes a sore throat
  • Fever

40.header: Did you feel your glands swollen before all these started?

41.header:
Yes?
This is a warning sign of a cold sore.

Warning signs include:

  • Tingling or burning near the lips or mouth area
  • Itching of the lips or skin around the mouth
  • Sometimes a sore throat
  • Fever
  • Sometimes swollen glands

42.header: Have you been around someone with a cold sore for the past 3 weeks?

43.header:
You have?
Chances of a cold sore is high.

Cold sore is very contagious.

44.header:
Alright.
Those were the warning signs of a cold sore.

Let's see if you need to see a doctor for this or if you can take care of it with a pharmacist's recommended over-the-counter remedy.

50.header:
Is this an outbreak.

An outbreak is having many blisters at the same time.

Let's find out if this is the case.

51.header: Are you looking at small blisters that grew together into a large blister?

53.header: What about small red blisters that break open and leak?

55.header: Are you seeing blisters filled with clear yellowish fluid?

57.header:
OK.
Have you been diagnosed with cold sore by a doctor before?

Or this is your first time experiencing cold sores?

58.header:
Diagnosed?
Continue with what worked for you in the past.

If you:

  • Used a prescription medication before:
    Call the doctor for a refill or a new prescription. Doctors are aware of re-occurences and you may not have to go in to see the doctor.

  • Still have the cream or pills you were prescribed last time:
    See if they are not expired and use them as per the previous directions

  • Have no doctor at the moment:
    Continue to see what a pharmacist recommends over-the-counter until you can see a doctor.

  • Used an over-the-counter cream previously and it worked fine:
    Repeat it. It should work as before.

Would you like to see what a pharmacist recommend you use over the counter or visit the nearest urgent care clinic?

59.header:
First time?
See a doctor when experiencing this for the first time.

You have to be sure what you're dealing with.

If you are sure it is cold sore you are looking at, let's see a pharmacist for an over-the-counter recommendation.

If after 2 weeks, there is no improvement or you've had this cold sore for 2 weeks now and there is no improvement, you must see a doctor.

Would you like to see what a pharmacist recommend or visit the nearest urgent care clinic for help?

19.title: Canker Sores
dlg:
Canker sores develop on soft tissues in the mouth such as on the tongue, inner lips, inside the cheeks or floor of the mouth. If the sore is on the outer part of the lips or side of the mouth, you will be looking at a cold sore (fever blisters).

Canker sore (inside the mouth) would cause a burning sensation or pain and this can last for about one week.

0.header:
A canker sore
is an open sore formed on soft tissues inside the mouth.

Let's see what is available over the counter to take care of canker sores.

1.header:
First, do you need to see a doctor for this canker sore?

It would be important to rule out anything major that may be causing it such as drug allergies, any kind of allergy or viral infection.

2.header: Do you also have fever with this sore in the mouth?

3.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible viral infection going on.

4.header: What about swollen lymph nodes?

5.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible viral or bacteria infection

6.header: Do you have a skin rash with this canker sore?

7.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible allergic reaction.

8.header: What about diarrhea with this canker sore?

9.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible viral infection
  • Dehydration is possible

10.header: Is this your third or more canker sore this year?

11.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need complete evaluation as to the cause.

12.header: Is this mouth sore so bad that you can hardly eat or drink?

13.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • If you can hardly eat, drink or swallow for instance, you will need a magic mouthwash that includes lidocaine. You need a prescription for this.

14.header:
Continuing assumes you don't think you need to see a doctor.

Before you see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter, let's see if you are looking at a canker sore to begin with.

20.header:
In front of a mirror, take a look at the affected area.
Do you see one or more painful red spots or bumps?

21.header:
Yes?
May be the beginning of the formation of the canker sore.

Usually, this red spots or bumps would develop into an open ulcer very soon.

22.header:
Do you see a sore with a middle that is white or yellow?

This may be surrounded by a bright, slightly raised red margins.

23.header:
OK.
Most likely looking at a canker sore.

24.header:
What about a gray area?

Sore may turn gray just before starting to heal.

25.header:
Yes?
They must have started to heal or are about to start healing.

Let's see what may have caused it.

26.header:
No?
Oh well, we just described the signs of a canker sore.

If you are still thinking canker sore, would you like to continue or seek urgent care?

30.header: What do you think may have caused it?

options.title: Mouth injury due to dental work

30.except: Oops!, You told me nothing

31.header:
No idea?
Well, let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter for relief.

32.header:
Stress?
Hope you are doing something about this.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter for relief or do you think you should seek urgent care from the discussions so far?

33.header:
Medication?
Some medications have canker sore as a side effect.

Examples are:

  • Beta-blockers
  • Antioxidants
  • NSAIDS
  • Antibiotics like cipro, ceftin, minocycline
  • Alendronate (fosamax), risedronate, ibandronate
  • Bupropion (wellbutrin), Effexor, Paxil, Zoloft
  • Taking echinacea, feverfew
  • Iron salts
  • Sleeping pills like Ambien, Lunesta
  • Others include Tacrolimus, Ropinirole, Seroquel, Zonisamide

Discuss this cankersore side effect with the doctor. Let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter for relief or do you think you should go to a nearby urgent care clinic from the discussions so far?

34.header:
Sorry about that.
Let's see what a pharmacist recommend over-the-counter for canker sore.

Or do you think you should go to a nearby urgent care clinic from the discussions so far?
